                    "company": "Leiden University",
                    "description": "My current research project - Global Jewish Philanthropy: Partners in Solidarity 1918-1948\n\nBelow is a brief description-\nThis project is a study of the relationship between European, North American, and Middle Eastern Jewry in the period between 1918 and 1948. Its main objective is to understand how disparate Jewish communities interacted through philanthropic networks in the post-WWI period until the creation of the state of Israel. Between 1918-1948 transnational Jewish solidarity organizations, based in Europe and North America expanded their presence in MENA by local Jewish groups in the development of communal infrastructure. As a result, interaction between Jewish sub-groups (i.e. Ashkenazi, Sephardi, Baghdadi, Maghrebi) increased exponentially often via national Jewish organisations (for example the AJA, AIU, and JDC). It is my hypothesis that these organisations transformed notions of Jewish identity, religiosity, and solidarity from the local to the global. In order to understand the nature of these transformations I will focus on Jewish religious reform, political participation, and acculturation through the lens of transnational solidarity movements.",
                    "title": "Lecturer and Postdoctoral Research Fellow ",
                    "employment_type": null
                },
                {
                    "location": "Leiden",
                    "date": {
                        "start": {
                            "month": 8,
                            "day": null,
                            "year": 2012
                        },
                        "end": {
                            "month": 10,
                            "day": null,
                            "year": 2018
                        }
                    },
                    "company": "Leiden University",
                    "description": "Member of the research group - \u201cArabic and its alternatives: religious minorities in the formative years of the Modern Middle East (1920-1950)\u201d.\n\nMy specific case study researches the Jewish Community of Baghdad.\n\nThis project aims to revisit the ways in which religious minorities in the Middle East participated in, contributed to, and opposed the Arab nationalism of the post-war\nyears, when the British and French ruled the region via the Mandates. This period of societal modernization and competing nationalisms saw the emergence of new political structures that would define the Middle East for most of the twentieth century. While Arabic nationalism, predicated as it was on the Arabic language more than on Islam, was seen as a positive development by many Arabic-speaking Jews and Christians, others showed increasing uneasiness with its ramifications. This was more specifically the case among those non-Muslims that in addition to Arabic highly valued other languages, such as Syriac, Hebrew and Armenian, but also English and French. Would participation in Arab nationalism also imply giving up the allegiances symbolized by these languages?",
                    "title": "PhD Candidate",
                    "employment_type": null
                }
            ]
        },
